    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Gesture of Joy'</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stanley Cook letter says he would have a certain amount of respect for Columbia University Prof Edward W Said, who hurled rock toward Israeli guardhouse from Lebanese border in July (Oct 19 article), if he had also thrown stone at or otherwise expressed his opposition to Syrian troops that still occupy Lebanon</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Columbia Debates a Professor's 'Gesture' '' (news article, Oct. 19) includes a photograph of Edward W. Said throwing a stone at Israeli soldiers, an act that he described as ''a symbolic gesture of joy'' that the Israeli occupation of southern Lebanon had ended.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Columbia Debates a Professor's 'Gesture' '' (news article, Oct. 19) includes a photograph of Edward W. Said throwing a stone at Israeli soldiers, an act that he described as ''a symbolic gesture of joy'' that the Israeli occupation of southern Lebanon had ended.</p>
        <p>I would have a certain amount of respect for Mr. Said if, while in Lebanon, he had also thrown a stone at or otherwise expressed his opposition to the Syrian troops that still occupy that country.</p>
        <p>STANLEY COOK  New Orleans, Oct. 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
